Modeling Wine Preferences by Data Mining and Physicochemical Properties

Jad Istanbelly

Description

The data sets used in this project comprise of wine quality and their characteristics. There are two data sets:

  1. Red wine and its physicochemical properties
  2. White wine and its physicochemical properties

Let us take a look at them below

There are two questions we will attempt to answer using these data sets:

  1. Can we build a model that can predict white wine quality?
    • Using parametric and non-parametric methods
  2. Can we build a model that can predict the wine type between red and white?
    • Using parametric and non-parametric methods

Downloading and Preparing Data

This data is publicly available at UCI.

The first step that we need to do is to load our data into R and prepare/clean it before manipulating anything. Data cleaning is a very important step to ensure the quality of your data and to avoid any mistakes caused by unorganized or messy information.

Important Notes before Analysis

  1. All the models used in this document will be Bagged, run under loops for hundreds or thousands of times. This is done to maintain consistency/minimize over-fitting and to lower variance caused by randomly splitting data in train and test sets.

  2. I will be tuning Hyper-parameters for each model if possible using a grid of parameter values. This is not a necessary step as it takes more computing power and time depending on specifications of your machine. However, it can increase accuracy so even a small to moderate sized grid search may help.

  3. Our procedure for analysis will follow these steps:

    • Estimate Models and pick the top model by using AUC or RMSPE

    • Identify most important predictors in the top model

    • Report final decision by testing the top model with the test set

  4. There are a lot of sections that contain a description earlier on in the document but not found in the later sections. This is simply to limit repetitive writing as most steps or code are very similar. If I have missed something that you would like clarification on please let me know!

Predicting White Wine Quality

We can tackle this question differently depending on how we want to identify the problem. For instance:

  1. Regression models will consider our dependent variable “Quality” as a continuous numeric variable and we will use Root Mean Square Percentage Error (RMSPE) and its uncertainty (SD) as metrics to make a final decision.

  2. Classification models will split “Quality” into categories of “less than average” and “better than average”. We will use Area Under Curve (AUC) and its uncertainty (SD) as metrics to make a decision.

Regression Problem

When working with a regression problem, we will be attempting to predict actual values of Quality.

For example; a white wine with, alcohol of 8, density of 1, pH of 3.5, etc. is predicted to be a quality of 7. This would also be known as Y and Y-hat or Actual and Predicted values.

Splitting Data

Before we can estimate models we have to split our data into test and train subsets. The idea is to keep the test subset aside for our top model and so we will be further splitting our initial train set once more to assist us with validating and comparing our models first.

# First Train and Test Split

ind <- sample(nrow(dfw), nrow(dfw)*0.90, replace = FALSE)
train <- dfw[ind, ]

# Save for later 

test <- dfw[-ind, ]

Estimating Models

Now we can run create and test various parametric and non-parametric models to determine which best suits our question.

Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

OLS is used as a benchmark in comparison to other models in this document therefore, a linear multivariate regression is run to start our testing.

\[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \beta_3 x_3 ... \beta_n x_n \]

library(DT)

# Set n for number of bags

n <- 500

# Empty containers are needed before loop starts 

RMSPE0 <- c()

# Create Loop 

for (i in 1:n) {

# cat("loops: ", i, "\r") 
  # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
  
# Randomly split Original Train Data
  
  ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE)
  train1 <- train[ind1, ]
  test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
  
# Create Model for each loop
  
  model0 <- lm(quality~., data = train1) 
  
# Predict Model for each loop
  
  yhat0 <- predict(model0, test1)
  
# Calculate RMSPE for each loop
  
  RMSPE0[i] <- sqrt(mean((test1$quality - yhat0)^2))
  
}

# Mean of RMSPE

MRMSPE0 <- mean(RMSPE0)

# Standard Deviation of RMSPE

uncer0 <- sqrt(var(RMSPE0) * n / (n - 1))

# Create results DF to compare at the end of testing

results <- cbind.data.frame(MRMSPE0, uncer0)

# Change colnames

colnames(results) <- c("MRMSPE", "SD" )

# Create row name vector for results DF

rnames <- "OLS"

# Showcase results

formatPercentage(datatable(results, rownames = FALSE), columns = c("MRMSPE", "SD"), digits = 2)

Classification and Regression Tree (CART)

Tuning Hyper-parameters

There are several Hyper-parameters using single decision trees, I have listed the ones I tuned below:

  1. Complexity Parameter (CP) = The value that each split must increase the overall \(R^2\) of the model by or else will be pruned.

  2. Min split (MS) = The minimum amount of observations allowed per node before attempting to split

  3. Max Depth (MD) = The maximum length taken from the root node to a leaf node, the tree will stop growing if MD is met.

library(rpart)

# Number of loops

n <- 5 

# Create Hyper-parameters

CP <- seq(0.01, 0.3, 0.01)
MS <- c(100, 300, 500, 750, 900)
MD <- 1:30

# Input Hyper-parameters into matrix and form a grid

grid <- as.matrix(expand.grid(MD, MS, CP))

# Create Empty Containers to store Loops Results
mse <-c()
sdmse <-c()

# Start of Loops
for(i in 1:nrow(grid)) {
  test_mse <- c() # Store calculated MSE from each loop
  for (j in 1:n) {
    try({
      # cat("loops: ", i, j,"\r") 
        # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
    
      # Second CV
      ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE) 
      train1 <- train[ind1, ]
      test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
      
      # Create model for each loop
      cart <- rpart(quality~., 
                    minsplit = grid[i, 2], cp = grid[i, 3], maxdepth = grid[i, 1], 
                    data = train1, method = "anova")
      
      # Predict Y-hats for each loop
      cartpr <- predict(cart, test1)
      
      # Calculate MSE for each loop
      test_mse[j] <- mean((test1$quality - cartpr)^2)
    })
  }
  # Find Mean and SD of all MSE's
  mse[i] <- mean(test_mse)
  sdmse[i] <- sd(test_mse)
}
# Create table and showcase results
# Find the Hyper-parameters that give the lowest MSE

tunedcart <- rbind(c(grid[which.min(mse), ], min(mse), mean(sdmse)))
colnames(tunedcart) <- c("MD", "MS", "CP","MMSE", "SD")
formatPercentage(datatable(tunedcart), columns = c("MMSE", "SD"), digits = 2)

K-Nearest Neighbors

Tuning Hyper-parameters

There is a single hyper-parameter that has been tuned using KNN, this would be:

  1. K = number of neighbors considered when evaluating the average value of a new data point
library(caret)

# Number of loops
n <- 5 

# Create Hyper-parameter

k <- seq(from = 2, to = sqrt(nrow(train1)), by = 1) # Number of neighbors considered

# Create Empty Containers to store Loops Results
mse <-c()
sdmse <-c()

# Start of Loops
for(i in 1:length(k)){
  test_mse <- c() # Store calculated MSE from each loop
  for (j in 1:n) {
    try({
      # cat("loops: ", i, j,"\r") 
        # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
    
      # Second CV
      ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE) 
      train1 <- train[ind1, ]
      test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
      
      # Create model for each loop
      knnt <- knnreg(quality~., data = train1, k = k[i])
      # Predict Y-hats for each loop
      knnpr <- predict(knnt, test1, method = "knn")
      
      # Calculate MSE for each loop
      test_mse[j] <- mean((test1$quality - knnpr)^2)
    })
  }
  # Find Mean and SD of all MSE's
  mse[i] <- mean(test_mse)
  sdmse[i] <- sd(test_mse)
}
# Create table and showcase results
# Find the Hyper-parameters that give the lowest MSE

tunedknn <- rbind(c(k[which.min(mse)], min(mse), mean(sdmse)))
colnames(tunedknn) <- c("K","MMSE", "SD")
formatPercentage(datatable(tunedknn), columns = c("MMSE", "SD"), digits = 2)

Random Forest (RF)

Tuning Hyper-parameters

There are several possible parameters to tune, these are the ones that I have experimented with:

  1. Number of Trees (NT) = Number of trees to grow in a forest

  2. Number of Variables (MT) = Amount of variables that are randomly selected at each split

library(ranger) # Ranger is a much faster/optimized RF package over "randomForest" 

# Number of loops

n <- 5 

# Create Hyper-parameters

NT <- seq(1000, 2000, 200) # Number of Trees
p <- ncol(train1)-1 # Amount of x-variables
MT <- p/3:p # p/3 is default for regression

# Input Hyper-parameters into matrix and form a grid

grid <- as.matrix(expand.grid(NT, MT))

# Create Empty Containers to store Loops Results
mse <-c()
sdmse <-c()

# Start of Loops
for(i in 1:nrow(grid)){
  test_mse <- c() # Store calculated MSE from each loop
  for (j in 1:n) {
    try({
       # cat("loops: ", i, j,"\r") 
        # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
    
      # Second CV
      ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE) 
      train1 <- train[ind1, ]
      test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
      
      # Create model for each loop
      rft <- ranger(y = train1[, 12], x = train1[, 1:11],
                          num.trees = grid[i, 1], mtry = grid[i, 2]) 
      
      # Predict Y-hats for each loop
      rfpr <- predict(rft, test1)
      
      # Calculate MSE for each loop
      test_mse[j] <- mean((test1$quality - rfpr$predictions)^2)
    })
  }
  # Find Mean and SD of all MSE's
  mse[i] <- mean(test_mse)
  sdmse[i] <- sd(test_mse)
}
# Create table and showcase results
# Find the Hyper-parameters that give the lowest MSE

tunedrf <- rbind(c(grid[which.min(mse), ], min(mse), mean(sdmse)))
colnames(tunedrf) <- c("NT","MT", "MMSE", "SD")
formatPercentage(datatable(tunedrf), columns = c("MMSE", "SD"), digits = 2)

Boosting

Tuning Hyper-parameters

The hyper-parameters tuned are:

  1. Shrinkage (SH) = The rate at which each expansion step is reduced by, this is also known as the learning rate

  2. N.Trees (NT) = Total number of trees to fit

  3. Interaction Depth (ID) = Number of splits in each tree

library(gbm)

# Number of loops

n <- 5 

# Create Hyper-parameters

SH <- seq(0.01, 0.3, 0.01) # Shrinkage default = 0.1
NT <- c(100, 300, 500, 750, 900) # Number of predicted trees default = 100
ID <- 1:sqrt(ncol(train1)) # Interaction Depth default = 1

# Input Hyper-parameters into matrix and form a grid

grid <- as.matrix(expand.grid(ID, NT, SH))

# Create Empty Containers to store Loops Results
mse <-c()
sdmse <-c()

# Start of Loops
for(i in 1:nrow(grid)) {
  test_mse <- c() # Store calculated MSE from each loop
  for (j in 1:n) {
    try({
      # cat("loops: ", i, j,"\r") 
        # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
    
      # Second CV
      
      ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE) 
      train1 <- train[ind1, ]
      test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
      
      # Create model for each loop
      
      boos <- gbm(quality~., distribution ="gaussian", n.trees=1000,
            interaction.depth = grid[i,1], shrinkage = grid[i,3], data = train1)
      
      # Predict Y-hats for each loop
      
      prboos <- predict(boos, test1, n.trees = grid[i,2])
      
      # Calculate MSE for each loop
      
      test_mse[j] <- mean((test1$quality - prboos)^2)
    })
  }
  # Find Mean and SD of all MSE's
  
  mse[i] <- mean(test_mse)
  sdmse[i] <- sd(test_mse)
}
# Create table and showcase results
# Find the Hyper-parameters that give the lowest MSE

tunedboost <- rbind(c(grid[which.min(mse), ], min(mse), mean(sdmse)))
colnames(tunedboost) <- c("ID", "NT", "SH", "MMSE", "SD")
formatPercentage(datatable(tunedboost), columns = c("MMSE", "SD"), digits = 2)

results[which.min(results$MRMSPE), ]

## RF 0.6267665 0.01424195

Looks like Random Forest is the model with the lowest RMSPE

Most Important Predictors

Below is a chart of our variables ranked based on their Node Impurity this refers to the remaining MSE after a variable is used to decrease MSE as a split in a tree. The idea is that important variables will reduce this impurity at a higher value (than other less important variables) and therefore, decreases overall MSE in return.

# Create DF of Variable Importance

imppred <- as.data.frame(model3$variable.importance)
colnames(imppred) <- "importance"

# Plot values on Bar graph

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(imppred, aes(x=reorder(row.names(imppred),importance), y=importance,fill=importance))+ 
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge")+ coord_flip()+
  ylab("Variable Importance")+
  xlab("")+
  ggtitle("Node Impurity")+
  guides(fill=F)+
  scale_fill_gradient(low="light blue", high="blue")

We now know which variables help decrease RMSPE in the model and thus better explains “Quality”, we would not want to omit the Top variables from our analysis.

Running Test on Winner

Since we only have 10% of the data to use to test our top model, we can cross-validate and shuffle the original split to retrieve new 10% sets of data to run on. Essentially, we are bagging the top model once more using the full set of data rather than the smaller portion used for validating.

# Set N for number of bags

n <- 500

# Empty containers are needed before loop starts 

RMSPEW <- c()

# Create Loop 

for (i in 1:n) {

# cat("loops: ", i, "\r") 
  # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
  
# Second CV
  ind <- sample(nrow(dfw), nrow(dfw)*0.90, replace = FALSE)
  train <- dfw[ind, ]
  test <- dfw[-ind1, ]
  
# Create Model for each loop
  
  modelw <- ranger(y = train[, 12], x = train[, 1:11],
                         num.trees = tunedrf[1], mtry = tunedrf[3]) 
  
# Predict Model for each loop
  
  yhatw <- predict(modelw, test)
  
# Calculate RMSPE for each loop
  
  RMSPEW[i] <- sqrt(mean((test$quality - yhatw$predictions)^2))
  
}

# Mean of RMSPE

MRMSPEW <- mean(RMSPEW)

# Standard Deviation of RMSPE

uncerw <- sqrt(var(RMSPEW) * n / (n - 1))

# Create DF of Winner Root Mean Square Prediction Error

resultsw <- cbind.data.frame("Model" = "Random Forest", "RMSPE" = MRMSPEW, "SD" = uncerw)

formatPercentage(datatable(resultsw), columns = c("RMSPE", "SD"), digits = 2)

Classification Problem

When working with a Classification problem, we will be attempting to predict classes/groups of Quality.

For example; a white wine with, alcohol of 8, density of 1, pH of 3.5, etc. is predicted to be above average in Quality.

Pre-processing Steps

As mentioned previously, we will split “Quality” to a Binary variable with the following outcomes:

  1. Below Average
  2. Above Average

Then create our initial test and train split

remove(list = ls())

Classification and Regression Tree (CART)

Tuning Hyper-parameters

The same parameters are tuned here as with the regression example above except for a slight change in definition for CP:

  • The Complexity Parameter is the minimum improvement needed at each node of the model or else it will be pruned.
library(rpart)
library(DT)
# Number of loops

n <- 5 

# Create Hyper-parameters

CP <- seq(0.01, 0.3, 0.01) # Complexity Parameter
MS <- c(100, 300, 500, 750, 900) # Min Split
MD <- 1:30 # Max Depth

# Input Hyper-parameters into matrix and form a grid

grid <- as.matrix(expand.grid(MD, MS, CP))

# Create Empty Containers to store Loops Results

mauc1 <- c()
sdauc1 <- c()

# Start of Loops
for(i in 1:nrow(grid)) {
  auc1 <- c() # Store calculated AUC from each loop
  for (j in 1:n) {
    try({
      # cat("loops: ", i, j,"\r") 
        # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
    
      # Second CV
      ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE) 
      train1 <- train[ind1, ]
      test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
      
      # Create model for each loop
      cart <- rpart(quality~., 
                    minsplit = grid[i, 2], cp = grid[i, 3], maxdepth = grid[i, 1], 
                    data = train1, method = "class")
      
      # Predict P-hats for each loop
      cartpr <- predict(cart, test1, type = "prob") [, 2]
      
      # Predict and Calculate AUC for each loop
      
      pred_rocr1 <- prediction(cartpr, test1$quality)
      auc_ROCR1 <- performance(pred_rocr1, measure = "auc")
      auc1[j] <- auc_ROCR1@y.values[[1]]
      
    })
  }
  # Find Mean and SD of all AUC's
  mauc1[i] <- mean(auc1)
  sdauc1[i] <- sd(auc1) 
}
# Create table and showcase results
# Find the Hyper-parameters that give the Max MAUC and Mean of SD

mmauc1 <- max(mauc1)
uncer1 <- mean(sdauc1) 

tunedcart <- rbind(c(grid[which.max(mauc1), ], mmauc1, uncer1))

Optimal Threshold and Confusion Table of winner

The Optimal Threshold (OT) let’s us know the best value to start the split between our two Classification groups. In this instance, OT will represent the value in which we should convert our probabilities to “above average” if greater than to OT.

The Confusion Table provides us with an understanding of our models’ classification success. We will be informed of information such as true positives/negatives and false positives/negatives, with this information we can derive further metrics such as Accuracy, Precision, Recall, etc. that can let us know how “correct” our model is in prediction.

library(scales)

grid <- phatw[order(phatw)] 
n <- length(grid)

TPR <- c()
FPR <- c()

for (i in 1:n) {
  yhat <- phatw > grid[i]
  ct <- table(yhat, test$quality)
  if(sum(dim(ct)) > 3){ 
    TPR[i] <- ct[2,2]/(ct[2,2]+ct[1,2])
    FPR[i] <- ct[2,1]/(ct[1,1]+ct[2,1])
  }
}

# Youden's J Statistics to convert phat into Y-hat

J <- TPR - FPR
opth <- grid[which.max(J)] 
opth
## [1] 0.6839516
# Convert P-hat to Y-hat using Optimal Threshold

yhat <- ifelse(phatw > opth, 1, 0)

# Confusion Table

ctable <- table(yhat, test$quality)

# Nicer Looking Confusion Table

rot <- function(x){
  t <- apply(x, 2, rev)
  tt <- apply(t, 1, rev)
  return(t(tt))
}
ct <- rot(ctable)
rownames(ct) <- c("Yhat = 1", "Yhat = 0")
colnames(ct) <- c("Y = 1", "Y = 0")
ct
##           
## yhat       Y = 1 Y = 0
##   Yhat = 1   949   146
##   Yhat = 0   266   467

Based on the confusion matrix our classes seem to be imbalanced and accuracy may not be the best measure. Therefore, let us compare Accuracy with F-1 Score to determine the level of bias ACC may have

The difference between these two metrics relay on that F-1 score takes into account, Recall and Precision whereas Accuracy does not.

# Accuracy

ACC <- sum(diag(ct))/sum(ct)
percent(ACC, accuracy = 0.01)
## [1] "77.46%"
# Recall 

REC <- ct[1, 1]/sum(ct[, 1])

# Precision

PRE <- ct[1, 1]/sum(ct[1, ])

# F-1 Score

F_1 <- 2*(PRE*REC/(PRE+REC))
percent(F_1, accuracy = 0.01)
## [1] "82.16%"

There is not a large difference between Accuracy and F-1. Either measure can be used however, Accuracy has a more direct interpretation.

Predicting Wine Type: Red or White

To predict wine type we will style our analysis using Classification . Our dependent variable is no longer “Quality”, it is “Type”.

Classification Problem

Before running our analysis we must prepare our data to fit our question, as mentioned above our predicted variable will be “Type” and we must create it.

To create “Type” we will do the following:

  1. Create a Binary outcome for Red Wines then for White Wines
  2. Combine both Data frames together into one larger data frame

  for (j in 1:n) {
    try({
      # cat("loops: ", i, j,"\r") 
        # Counter to keep track of loops when running (remove the # beside cat to use)
    
      # Second CV
      ind1 <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train), replace = TRUE) 
      train1 <- train[ind1, ]
      test1 <- train[-ind1, ]
      
      # Create model for each loop
      cart <- rpart(type~., minsplit = grid[i, 2], cp = grid[i, 3], 
                    maxdepth = grid[i, 1], 
                    data = train1, method = "class")
      
      # Predict P-hats for each loop
      cartpr <- predict(cart, test1, type = "prob") [, 2]

Optimal Threshold and Confusion Table of winner

grid <- phatw[order(phatw)] 
n <- length(grid)

TPR <- c()
FPR <- c()

for (i in 1:n) {
  yhat <- phatw > grid[i]
  ct <- table(yhat, test$type)
  if(sum(dim(ct)) > 3){ 
    TPR[i] <- ct[2,2]/(ct[2,2]+ct[1,2])
    FPR[i] <- ct[2,1]/(ct[1,1]+ct[2,1])
  }
}

# Youden's J Statistic to convert phat into yhat

J <- TPR - FPR
opth <- grid[which.max(J)] 
opth
## [1] 0.3898142
# Convert P-hat to Y-hat using Optimal Threshold

yhat <- ifelse(phatw > opth, 1, 0)

# Confusion Table

ctable <- table(yhat, test$type)

# Nicer Looking Confusion Table

rot <- function(x){
  t <- apply(x, 2, rev)
  tt <- apply(t, 1, rev)
  return(t(tt))
}
ct <- rot(ctable)
rownames(ct) <- c("Yhat = 1", "Yhat = 0")
colnames(ct) <- c("Y = 1", "Y = 0")
ct
##           
## yhat       Y = 1 Y = 0
##   Yhat = 1   580     5
##   Yhat = 0     9  1768

Based on the confusion matrix our classes seem to be imbalanced let us compare Accuracy with F-1 Score again

# Accuracy

ACC <- sum(diag(ct))/sum(ct)
percent(ACC, accuracy = 0.01)
## [1] "99.41%"
# Recall 

REC <- ct[1, 1]/sum(ct[, 1])

# Precision

PRE <- ct[1, 1]/sum(ct[1, ])

# F-1 Score

F_1 <- 2*(PRE*REC/(PRE+REC))
percent(F_1, accuracy = 0.01)
## [1] "98.81%"

Not a significant difference is found so either metric can be used. As mentioned previously, Accuracy is preferred due to it’s definition.
